**Two-Sample Z-Test for Coin Bias.** Coin A: 200 flips, 120 heads. Coin B: 150 flips, 90 heads. \begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph{*})]\item State $H_{0}$ and $H_{1}$ for equal bias.

\item Compute the test statistic and p-value.

\item At $\alpha=0.05$, state your conclusion.\end{enumerate}

**Power Calculation: Required Sample Size.** Test $H_{0}\colon\mu=0$ vs $H_{1}\colon\mu=1$ using a sample from $N(\mu,4)$ at $\alpha=0.05$. \begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph{*})]\item For $n=25$, what is the power of the test?

\item What $n$ is needed for power $\geq80\%$?

\item Sketch the power curve as a function of $n$.\end{enumerate}

**Multiple Testing: Bonferroni Correction.** A researcher runs 100 independent tests with $H_{0}$ true for all, using $\alpha=0.05$ per test. \begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph{*})]\item How many false positives are expected?

\item What is $\mathbb{P}(\text{at least one false positive})$?

\item What Bonferroni threshold $\alpha^{*}$ controls FWER at 5\%?\end{enumerate}

**One-Sided Drug Trial.** A drug manufacturer claims a new drug reduces blood pressure by at least 10 mmHg. You measure $n=25$ patients: mean reduction $\bar{x}=8.5$ mmHg, sample standard deviation $s=4$ mmHg. \begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph{*})]\item Set up the appropriate one-sided hypothesis test.

\item Compute the $t$-statistic.

\item Find the p-value and state your conclusion at $\alpha=5\%$.\end{enumerate}
